## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread when it exceeds a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work. The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Key Paradigm Shift

| .NET Framework (preemptive) | .NET 8 (cooperative) |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` forcibly injects an exception | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` sets a flag |
| Runtime kills the thread for you | **Your code must voluntarily check** the token |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload (preferred in modern .NET)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; `Task` integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Token auto-cancels after the timeout expires |
| `thread.Abort()` | Token cancellation | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No abort to reset — cancellation is cooperative |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must receive** the token to cooperate |

---

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is NOT automatic — the work must cooperate**

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: ignores the token — will never stop on timeout
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    Thread.Sleep(30000); // blocks, never checks token
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ GOOD: checks the token at regular intervals
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        DoChunkOfWork(i);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. Replace blocking calls with cancellation-aware alternatives**

```csharp
// ❌ Thread.Sleep ignores the token
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// ✅ Wakes immediately when cancelled
await Task.Delay(5000, cancellationToken);
// or synchronously:
cancellationToken.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

**3. Pass the token through the entire call chain**

```csharp
// ❌ Token stops propagating — downstream work can't be cancelled
async Task<Data> ProcessAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    var raw = await httpClient.GetAsync(url);  // no token!
    return Parse(raw);
}

// ✅ Every async call receives the token
async Task<Data> ProcessAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    var raw = await httpClient.GetAsync(url, token);
    return Parse(raw);
}
```

**4. Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`**

`CancellationTokenSource` with a timeout allocates an internal timer. The `using` statement in the migrated code handles this. Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks.

**5. Uncooperative code (can't modify to accept token)**

If you're calling code you don't control (e.g., a native library), cooperative cancellation won't help. Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
// Last resort for truly uncooperative work
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

---

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));

// After (.NET 8) — pass token into the work
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token => ComputeExpensiveResult(token),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter in the catch ensures that if the work itself throws `OperationCanceledException` for a *different* reason (e.g., a user-initiated cancellation token), it won't be misidentified as a timeout.
